[907.709461, "o", "\u001b[3;66H\\"]
[907.709712, "o", "\u001b[4;1Hrlying\u001b[K\u001b[5;1H‘chmod’ system call.  When in doubt, check the underlying system\u001b[6;1Hbehavior.\u001b[K\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K\u001b[8;1H   If used, MODE specifies the new file mode bits.  For details, \u001b[8;66H\\\u001b[9;1Hsee the\u001b[K\u001b[10;1Hsection on \u001b[4m*note File permissions\u001b[24m::.  If you really want MODE to \u001b[K\u001b[10;66H\\\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K\u001b[11;1Hhave a\u001b[12;1Hleading ‘-’, you should use ‘--’ first, e.g., ‘chmod -- -w file’.\u001b[13;1HTypically, though, ‘chmod a-w file’ is preferable, and ‘chmod -w \u001b[13;66H\\\u001b[14;1Hfile’\u001b[K\u001b[15;1H(without the ‘--’) complains if it behaves differently from what \u001b[15;66H\\\u001b[16;1H‘chmod\u001b[K\u001b[16;1H\u001b[1;66H\\\u001b[3;66H\\\u001b[8;66H\\\u001b[10;66H\\\u001b[13;66H\\\u001b[15;66H\\\u001b[16;1H"]
[907.740526, "o", "\u001b[16;1H\u001b[17;1H\u001b[7m-----Info: (coreutils)chmod invocation, 120 lines --34%-----------\u001b[0m\u001b[1;1Hed.\u001b[K\u001b[2;1HThis behavior depends on the policy and functionality of the unde\u001b[2;66H\\\u001b[3;1Hrlying\u001b[K\u001b[4;1H‘chmod’ system call.  When in doubt, check the underlying system\u001b[5;1Hbehavior.\u001b[K\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[7;1H   If used, MODE specifies the new file mode bits.  For details, \u001b[7;66H\\\u001b[8;1Hsee the\u001b[K\u001b[9;1Hsection on \u001b[4m*note File permissions\u001b[24m::.  If you really want MODE to \u001b[K\u001b[9;66H\\\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K\u001b[10;1Hhave a\u001b[11;1Hleading ‘-’, you should use ‘--’ first, e.g., ‘chmod -- -w file’."]
[907.740648, "o", "\u001b[12;1HTypically, though, ‘chmod a-w file’ is preferable, and ‘chmod -w \u001b[12;66H\\\u001b[13;1Hfile’\u001b[K\u001b[14;1H(without the ‘--’) complains if it behaves differently from what \u001b[14;66H\\\u001b[15;1H‘chmod\u001b[K\u001b[16;1Ha-w file’ would do.\u001b[16;1H\u001b[2;66H\\\u001b[7;66H\\\u001b[9;66H\\\u001b[12;66H\\\u001b[14;66H\\\u001b[16;1H"]
[907.771743, "o", "\u001b[16;1H"]
[907.771865, "o", "\u001b[17;1H\u001b[7m-----Info: (coreutils)chmod invocation, 120 lines --35%-----------\u001b[0m\u001b[1;1HThis behavior depends on the policy and functionality of the unde\u001b[1;66H\\\u001b[2;1Hrlying\u001b[K\u001b[3;1H‘chmod’ system call.  When in doubt, check the underlying system\u001b[4;1Hbehavior.\u001b[K\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[6;1H   If used, MODE specifies the new file mode bits.  For details, \u001b[6;66H\\\u001b[7;1Hsee the\u001b[K\u001b[8;1Hsection on \u001b[4m*note File permissions\u001b[24m::.  If you really want MODE to \u001b[K\u001b[8;66H\\\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K\u001b[9;1Hhave a\u001b[10;1Hleading ‘-’, you should use ‘--’ first, e.g., ‘chmod -- -w file’.\u001b[11;1HTypically, though, ‘chmod a-w file’ is preferable, and ‘chmod -w \u001b[11;66H\\\u001b[12;1Hfile’\u001b[K\u001b[13;1H(without the ‘--’) complains if it behaves differently from what \u001b[13;66H\\\u001b[14;1H‘chmod\u001b[K\u001b[15;1Ha-w file’ would do.\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K\u001b[16;1H\u001b[1;66H\\\u001b[6;66H\\\u001b[8;66H\\\u001b[11;66H\\\u001b[13;66H\\\u001b[16;1H"]
