[907.803748, "o", "\u001b[2;1H‘chmod’ system call.  When in doubt, check the underlying system\u001b[3;1Hbehavior.\u001b[K\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K\u001b[5;1H   If used, MODE specifies the new file mode bits.  For details, \u001b[5;66H\\\u001b[6;1Hsee the\u001b[K\u001b[7;1Hsection on \u001b[4m*note File permissions\u001b[24m::.  If you really want MODE to \u001b[K\u001b[7;66H\\\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[8;1Hhave a\u001b[9;1Hleading ‘-’, you should use ‘--’ first, e.g., ‘chmod -- -w file’."]
[907.803963, "o", "\u001b[10;1HTypically, though, ‘chmod a-w file’ is preferable, and ‘chmod -w \u001b[10;66H\\\u001b[11;1Hfile’\u001b[K\u001b[12;1H(without the ‘--’) complains if it behaves differently from what \u001b[12;66H\\\u001b[13;1H‘chmod\u001b[K\u001b[14;1Ha-w file’ would do.\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K\u001b[16;1H   The program accepts the following options.  Also see \u001b[1m*note Com\u001b[0m\u001b[K\u001b[16;66H\\\u001b[16;1H\u001b[5;66H\\\u001b[7;66H\\\u001b[10;66H\\\u001b[12;66H\\\u001b[16;66H\\\u001b[16;1H"]
